  "prompt": "How was the Alioth star named?",
  "response": "The name \"Alioth\" comes from the Arabic phrase \"al-\u2018ay\u1e0d al-\u2018a\u1e6d\u1e6da,\" which translates to \"the tail of the great one\" in reference to its position in the constellation Ursa Major, where it marks the tail of the Great Bear. In the context of historical star naming, many stars have Arabic origins due to the significant contributions of Arabic astronomers during the Islamic Golden Age. They preserved and advanced astronomical knowledge, and many of the names they assigned to stars are still used today. Alioth is the third-brightest star in Ursa Major and is known as Epsilon Ursae Majoris in the Bayer designation system.",
